<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Named after the Maya people, who used to live in the area. The name is to be regarded as a noun in apposition.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Diagnostic characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="81">The male can be distinguished from its congeners by the combination of: pale brown species; wing without markings; tergite IX without setose dorsal lobe(s) or spine; anal point spatulate; superior volsella slender, curved, tapering; gonostylus curved, with strong setae on protruberance on inner margin in basal one-third.</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1033.60686.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/534703" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" start="Figure 10" startId="F10">
